[read-mdn-doc](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Reference/Elements/video)


The `<video>` element in HTML5 is used to **embed video content** directly into web pages without the need for external plugins like Flash. It provides a standardized way to deliver video across modern browsers, supporting multiple formats and rich functionality through various attributes and JavaScript API.

---

### Purpose of the `<video>` Element

The `<video>` element is a **media tag** that enables websites to:

* Play embedded video files
* Offer playback controls (play, pause, volume, fullscreen)
* Support multiple formats for cross-browser compatibility
* Integrate with JavaScript for custom control

---

### Basic Syntax

```html
<video src="movie.mp4" controls=""></video>
```

---

### Full Structure Example

```html
<video width="640" height="360" controls="" autoplay="" muted="" loop="" poster="thumbnail.jpg">
  <source src="movie.mp4" type="video/mp4">
  <source src="movie.webm" type="video/webm">
  <source src="movie.ogv" type="video/ogg">
  Your browser does not support the video tag.
</video>
```

---

### All Attributes of `<video>`

| **Attribute**             | **Description**                                                                                     |
| ------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `src`                     | Specifies the path to the video file (can be used directly on `<video>` or inside `<source>` tags). |
| `controls`                | Displays built-in play, pause, volume, and seek controls.                                           |
| `autoplay`                | Video starts playing automatically once ready (muted must be used to autoplay in modern browsers).  |
| `muted`                   | Starts the video without sound. Often required for autoplay to work.                                |
| `loop`                    | Repeats the video once it ends.                                                                     |
| `poster`                  | URL of an image to show before the video starts or while itâ€™s downloading.                          |
| `preload`                 | Informs the browser how much data to preload: `auto`, `metadata`, or `none`.                        |
| `width`                   | Sets the width of the video player in pixels.                                                       |
| `height`                  | Sets the height of the video player in pixels.                                                      |
| `playsinline`             | Enables inline playback on mobile devices instead of full-screen.                                   |
| `crossorigin`             | Handles cross-origin requests for video files. Accepts `anonymous` or `use-credentials`.            |
| `disablepictureinpicture` | Prevents the video from being played in Picture-in-Picture mode (browser-specific).                 |

---

### `<source>` Tag Inside `<video>`

Using multiple `<source>` tags ensures browser compatibility:

```html
<video controls="">
  <source src="video.mp4" type="video/mp4">
  <source src="video.webm" type="video/webm">
  <source src="video.ogv" type="video/ogg">
  Your browser does not support the video tag.
</video>
```

* The browser picks the first format it supports.
* Always include a fallback message for unsupported browsers.

---

### Video Formats and MIME Types

| **Format** | **MIME Type** | **Browser Support**     |
| ---------- | ------------- | ----------------------- |
| `.mp4`     | `video/mp4`   | Universal (recommended) |
| `.webm`    | `video/webm`  | Chrome, Firefox, Opera  |
| `.ogv`     | `video/ogg`   | Firefox, Opera          |

---

### JavaScript API for `<video>`

You can control `<video>` elements using JavaScript:

```html
<video id="myVideo" src="movie.mp4" controls=""></video>


```

---

### Accessibility Considerations

* Use `captions` or `<track>` for subtitles:

```html
<video controls="">
  <source src="movie.mp4" type="video/mp4">
  <track src="subtitles_en.vtt" kind="subtitles" srclang="en" label="English">
</video>
```

* Always provide a **text fallback** for unsupported browsers.

---

### Common Use Cases

| **Use Case**         | **Example**                                       |
| -------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| Background video     | `<video autoplay="" muted="" loop="" playsinline=""></video>` |
| Learning platforms   | Use with `<track>` for subtitles and chapters     |
| Custom video players | Control via JavaScript and CSS for UI             |

---

### Summary Table

| **Tag**    | **Purpose**                         |
| ---------- | ----------------------------------- |
| `<video>`  | Embeds the video player             |
| `<source>` | Specifies alternative video sources |
| `<track>`  | Adds captions/subtitles/metadata    |

---

### Conclusion

The `<video>` element in HTML5 offers a powerful, flexible way to integrate video content directly into webpages. By supporting multiple formats, playback attributes, and accessibility features, it ensures consistent and user-friendly media delivery across all modern browsers.

